{"cursor":"3598","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Amos Vogel' (born Amos Vogelbaum; April 18, 1921 in Vienna – April 24,\n2012, in NY) was one of the most influential s in New York City. He is best\nknown for his bestselling book [[Film as a Subversive Art]] (1974) and as the\nfounder of the New York City avantgarde cinÃ©-club Cinema 16 (1947â1963), where\nhe was the first programmer to present films by Roman Polanski, John Cassavetes,\nNagisa Oshima, Jacques Rivette and Alain Resnais as well as early and important\nscreenings by American avant-gardists of the time like Stan Brakhage, Maya\nDeren, James Broughton, Kenneth Anger, Sidney Peterson, Bruce Conner, Carmen\nD'Avino and many others. In 1963, together with Richard Roud, he founded the New\nYork Film Festival, and served as its program director until 1968. In 1973,\nVogel started the Annenberg Cinematheque at the University of Pennsylvania and\nwas eventually given a Chair for film studies at the Annenberg School for\nCommunication, where he taught and lectured for two decades.\n\nVogel was born in Vienna, Austria. He fled Austria with his parents after the\nNazi AnschluÃ in 1938 and at first studied animal husbandry at the University of\nGeorgia. In the American South, he noted, the racism was as bad as the anti-\nsemitism he witnessed in Europe. Later he received a bachelor's degree from The\nNew School for Social Research in New York.\n\nVogel is also the author of a book for children, How Little Lori Visited Times\nSquare, published in 1963 with illustrations by Maurice Sendak.\n\nVogel participated in the documentary [[In the Mirror of Maya Deren]] (2003) by\nMartina KudlÃ¡cek. Vogel died, aged 91 on April 24, 2012, in New York\nCity.\n","linknr":129,"url":"Amos_Vogel","recorded":1374965781,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Amos_Vogel&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Amos_Vogel&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.ph